segments.text: We were talking about the trolley coming in from Bryan and I believe you mentioned on busy days they pulled a trailer.
Where did they store that trailer?
In Bryan just east of the
Location of the Brown Eagle, where the Brown Eagle is at present.
Do you remember how long that trolley continued to run?
I do not recall.
I know it was after you graduated.
I thought maybe since you had remained in the area, you would have perhaps remembered.
But that's a, it's not.
I remember when it discontinued, but I don't recall the year.
OK.
Were there other things that students did?
We've talked about going to Bryan.
We've talked about the movies, that there was a swimming pool in Hawaii.
There were sports, intramural sports or battalion sports.
What about inside their dormitories?
I know that they had a quiet hour during the evening when they had to study, but during the day, did they do anything inside for entertainment?
I don't recall, except perhaps card games, a few.
Some did a lot of sleeping, of course.
I had one roommate who had that reputation, but I guess that's what caused me to think about that.
Well, I know when I was in school, there were a number of boys who did a fair amount of sleeping during the afternoons.
Of course, at that point, they could do carousing at night, but I imagine you were controlled, so you really couldn't do much carousing at night.
It seems to me that the study was from 7.30 until 11 o'clock.
Taps are 11 o'clock.
Did you not have a...
tattoo and then a free period of a few minutes and then taps, or?
Yes.
You had that, huh?
Okay, so that was primarily kind of a preliminary warning that it was about time to go to bed, is that it?
That's right.
Okay.
Did you have any favorite instructors during your student days?
And if so, who were they and why?
Dr. Silvey, to me, was one of the outstanding instructors.
He was head of physics department, and I was fortunate in having him.
But I had many good instructors, I thought.
And in veterinary medicine, of course.
after I came back in the fall of 23 to take veterinary medicine, I thought Dr. Francis and Dr. Leonard were outstanding as instructors.
You mentioned coming back to vet medicine.
Before I finished, Dr. Biltsing, head of entomology, I thought was an excellent instructor.
Mr. Stangle, frequently called Runt Stangle, who is a retired dean of agriculture at Texas Tech, was outstanding.
There were many others.
What I was about to ask, at what point did you decide to go on for your degree in vet medicine?
I had a course under Dr. Francis in my junior year in animal husbandry and a course under Dr. Marsteller and Dr. Leonard in my senior year.
Those courses caused me to think that I would like to.
take veterinary medicine mainly as a good combination with animal husbandry, especially the course of Dr. Francis.
Then I finished in January 1926 and went to Beaumont until September the 10th, 1926.
You received your bachelor's in the spring of 23, right?
That's right, May 19, 23.
And came back the following fall and enrolled in vet medicine.
That's right.
Did you have to apply well in advance for vet medicine, or was there not the competition then as there is now?
Well, I don't know whether I've gotten in on the present conditions, but, requirements, but
No, I don't recall writing about it.
I just came in.
I knew that they would like to have some students.
I didn't have any difficulty at all.
Okay, let's get back to your undergraduate day for a minute.
We know that a lot of students had part-time employment while they were here.
Did you have any jobs of any sort?
Not while I was taking animal husbandry.
I did work and lived at the veterinary hospital from 1925-26.
So one year you lived in the hospital and worked there?
From June 1924 through January 1926.
At the point that you were in the school of vet medicine, were their semesters the same as the rest of the college?
Yes.
Okay, so you had summer off then?
Yes.
Did you have employment during the summers?
Well, in the summer of, I worked at home in the, except the summer of 21, I worked for Lackawanna Farms owned by Frank Schofield at Hillsboro on a shorthand.
farm.
It was a show herd.
I worked up there to gain some experience.
The other summers I worked at home on the farm.
One of the things that
I have felt that makes Texas A&M a somewhat unique institution of the traditions that are carried on by the student body, and now I suppose more by the Corps of Cadets than anybody else.
I think of things like y'all practice, silver taps, bonfire, such things as that.
Did you have
these things during your student days?
Yes.
We had silver taps and we had bonfires.
Where was the bonfire at the time you were a student?
Held in the center of the, what we called the old drill field out in front of the MSC, between MSC and Law and Prairie.
Was that all four years?
Yes.
What was the nature of the bonfire at that point?
What kind of materials did you make it out of?
A little of everything, but not on the big scale that they do now.
Was it done primarily by the freshmen, or did everybody pitch in and do some of it?
No, I think all the classes helped on it.
But it was a very small-scale affair, more of a trash fire.
A big bonfire.
Well, but even then it was for the University of Texas at Thanksgiving.
That is right.
Preceded the University of Texas.
What about a muster?
Did you have a muster on campus during your student days?
Not that I recall.
I noted in your senior yearbook that you were president of the Turkey Trot Club.
What was that organization?
Of course, being from Cuero, we were known as, that's where the original Turkey Trot was held, and the first one was held in 1912.
It's just the name of the county or the A&M Club.
It was actually a DeWitt County club.
So it was a hometown club?
Yes, a hometown club.
So you
indicated you finished your vet medicine degree in January?
January 1926.
Did you join the faculty here immediately then?
No, I went to Beaumont where I was in veterinary practice with Dr. J.G.
Kerr.
For how long?
until September the 10th.
I was supposed to start here in September the 1st, but Dr. Kerr was on vacation, the first vacation he had taken in years, and I didn't want to interrupt that.
I had had a letter from Dr. Francis in the middle of August.
He had a resignation.
in the staff and asked if I was interested.
He said, don't use the telephone.
He, of course, was hard of hearing.
So I got busy.
I was going from 5 or 6 in the morning till 11 o'clock at night.
And then I had a telephone call from Dr. Marsteller asking me when I was going to answer that letter.
Or when I decided, I said, I'm not qualified, Dr. Marsteller.
I'd like to take some graduate work.
And I'd like to take it for about three years.
And so he said, well, I'll tell the dean.
And I said, well, I'll get a note off time.
And after he talked to me.
So I've been here ever since.
How did you resolve your feeling that you weren't qualified and your decision finally to accept the position?
Well, I took some summers off and went to Iowa State, what is now Iowa State University at Ames and the University of Chicago.
the University of Michigan and the University of Texas, and took some specialized courses.
In vet medicine?
No.
At Iowa State, I took poisonous plants and physical chemistry and the biochemistry that was offered to veterinary students.
They had a summer class that year.
And the physical chemistry was really biophysical, which I used a great deal after I came back.
At the University of Michigan, I took courses in physiology and physiological chemistry, those two courses.
At the University of Chicago, I took physiology and biochemistry.
At the University of Texas, I took physics.
Having had physics here with Dr. Silvey, I thought perhaps that

I was going a little bit too strong in biochemistry for our physiology students, and I decided I'd take a course in physics to see if there were any new developments so that I wouldn't lean too heavily on the chemistry part.
After all, physiology is a combination of physics and chemistry.
that's applied, physics and chemistry.
I still didn't think I had enough graduate work, but I got too busy.
I believe, what, you've been here, what, nine years when you became head of the, no, yeah, head of the department and professor.
35, yes.
In veterinary physiology and pharmacology.
That's right.
And you held that position until you retired then in 67.
Well, I was head until through 1966.
Uh-huh.
And then I was a professor in the department from September 1, 1966 through August 31, 1967.
So you stepped down as head and taught one more year.
Yes.
As head of the department, how much teaching did you do?
I don't recall the number of hours.
In some cases, over 20 hours.
sometimes with as many as four courses.
We had heavy teaching loads.
With a smaller... And later on, as I got help, the first help I got was in 1936.
And then when I retired in 66, I think there were
Four of us, as I recall.
So the department grew from one to four?
Oh yes, now it's about 15 or 16 of them.
Oh gracious.
Has the student body increased that much since 67 to justify that?
Well, they've gone from 64 students to 128.
So it's doubled.
Yes.
In just, since 66?
At least more than double, I'd say.

What I was starting to say earlier, since you have a smaller student body in the School of Appomattox and now the College of Appomattox, and you did not have as much administrative responsibility, say, as the head of the Department of Civil Engineering.
Oh, no, far from it.
If a student in medicine, does he major in one of the departments in the school or college?
No, not through the three years of trimesters.
No, there's no specialization.
Specialization.
Specialization will come only in graduate work.
In other words, if he would come back for a PhD in vet medicine, then he would come back for, say, a PhD major in physiology and pharmacology or veterinary surgery?
Well, it's physiology and toxicology now.
Toxicology is handled in the physiology department.
There's a Ph.D. in Physiology and there's a Ph.D. in Toxicology.
And then they have Ph.D.s in the other departments, Anatomy and Microbiology, Pathology, Public Health.
But when you joined the Vet Medicine faculty in 26, you were the only one
in the area of physiology and pharmacology.
Correct.
And you remained that for ten years, right?
I believe you said in 1936 you finally got some help.
That's right.
Let me start all over again.
When you, particularly in your early years of teaching, did you have some research responsibilities in addition to your teaching load?
No.
What about during the summers?
Did you do research then?
Yes, yes we could.
We had courses sometimes offered in the summer.
One summer, I taught a course for Dr. Francis and two students, a course on anatomy and physiology.
This would be not medicine students.
No.
This would be like animal husbandry or students in Texas A&M College.
As opposed to the School of Vet Medicine?
That's right, service courses.
Uh-huh.
Did, while you were...
However, we had some courses offered in the summer for repeaters.
I do not recall how many.
I think it took five to get a course in the summertime.
We had some summer classes that way.
That would have been fairly infrequent, though, I take it.
Yes.
Well, let me back this up again.
You mentioned earlier having like maybe as many as 20 hours of teaching load.
More than 20.
More than 20.
How much of that was in the School of Vet Medicine and how much of that was to undergraduates?
Most of it in veterinary medicine.
I had one service course for animal husbandry students.
And then Dr. Ball wanted to offer a course in physiology for biology majors and pre-med students.
And we had a double entry on those two courses, 341, 342.
They were in biology 341, biology 342.
And the same course was VPP 341, VPP 342.
But I did the teaching entirely, except one year, I think that was in 32, I believe, John Milliff handled it that year.
And then...
When Penberthy came here in the fall of 26, they got interested in developing a curriculum for physical education.
And Mr. Friely, who was registrar and dean of the graduate college, asked me to work up a course
And I work up the course, and he said, now will you teach it?
So I fell out to the physical ed, the way I handled it.
We signed them up for 341.
And then they would drop out after one semester.
And then the science students and pre-med students would continue into 342.
So that didn't make it so hard.
Did you continue teaching in both medicine students and undergraduates through your whole career?
That's right.
Right.
However, in the last few years, I handled the animal husbandry, the service course to animal husbandry majors and dairy science majors and poultry science majors.
and the course in toxicology.
I think the last course in veterinary physiology I handled was to the class that graduated in 53 or 54, something like that.
Is that a general practice throughout the
current College of Vet Medicine that people out there teach both vet students and undergraduates?
Not necessarily, no.
Some of them teach solely veterinary students.
In the physiology department, for example, I think Dr. Claiborne handles the ag students.
And some of them teach pharmacology alone.
And some teach only physiology and have several in that category.
Well, of course, with the tremendous growth in student enrollment, why I think this probably permits more specialization of the faculty.
It's much better now than it used to be.
And you mentioned earlier there were
Did you say a hundred and how many students?
We went from 64 to 128.
And then do you have people working on a PhD in vet medicine in addition to that?
Oh yes, they are not counted in that 128.
Those are the ones who enter on the trimester basis.
Working on their PhD, they would work on the semester basis.
I see.
They enrolled through the regular graduate school?
Yes.
I see.
Okay.
We teach the service courses like town husbandry.
or Animal Science now.
That's on a semester basis.
I teach on semester and trimester both.
So you kind of have to keep your time straight.
That's right.
And graduate courses on semester.
Are your service courses that you taught for both graduates and undergraduates?
Yes, I had a graduate course on several occasions, but most of them were undergraduates.
I had an old newspaper clipping, I think, about the time you retired.

I think it was a write-up about a party which they gave for you, and I believe I've got this quoted fairly directly here that said, you were best known for development of toxicology through which you made national contributions and designed a reference system made available to students.
What kind of reference system was this?
Mainly a card index file.
that was free for students to use.
And they would come in and use it.
They were free to use it.
I had it on my desk.
They were as free to use it as I was.
This would be a file where if they had needed information on a specific topic, they could come check the index file, and this would guide them to the source material.
That's right.
Does that system still exist over in the School of Medicine?
I do not know.
You didn't take it with you when you left?
Yes, I took it with me because I have been on several consulting cases.
I see.
And that was my source of information.
And one was a court case, and the other one was, I don't know whether it's still pending or not,
But I needed those cards for that purpose or they'll eventually end up out there.
